Radio presenter and actress Masechaba Ndlovu nearly fell into the hands of scammers, but was clever enough to see through their dumb actions.This after the Metro FM drive time co-host was almost swindled of R85 000 during a WhatsApp conversation with a stranger.According to a police statement she deposed at the Randburg cop shop, the 34-year-old verified the message by calling her sister first, only to find out it wasn’t her.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>She said the message was received when she was enjoying the comforts of her home in Bryanston, north of Jozi.“The complainant alleged that she received a message from her cellphone from an unknown person, who pretended to be her sister and tried to defraud her of R85 000,” reads the statement.Police spokesperson Makgowanyana Maja said no suspects had been arrested and investigations were still on.When contacted for comment, The Drive co-presenter confirmed that she saw red lights when the alleged “ghost” tried to con her.“Yes, I can confirm that the incident took place. I don’t know why people try these horrible things. I hope police can put a stop to it,” she said.The seasoned broadcaster also said it was the first time such an incident had happened to her, and cautioned people to be on high alert for scammers.